Rating: 4
As one who has Indian heritage and experience cooking various curries, there are some obvious things missing. Here is the recipe the way I did it and to the delight of many Indian friends and family... now it's a 4 star recipe: 1 1/4 lb small fresh okra, left untrimmed, or 2 (10-oz) packages frozen whole okra (not thawed) 1 1/2 tablespoons vegetable oil (substitute butter to make much it tastier) 1 medium onion, chopped 4 garlic cloves, finely chopped 4 teaspoons finely chopped peeled fresh ginger 1 Tablespoon curry powder 1 (14- to 15-oz) can whole tomatoes in juice, tomatoes chopped, reserving juice 1 (19-oz) can chickpeas, drained and rinsed (2 cups) 2/3 cup chicken broth (use the broth from the can of chicken breasts) 3/4 teaspoon salt 1/4-1 teaspoon whole black pepper corns 3 whole cloves 1/8-3/4 teaspoon chili powder (to taste) 3 large bay leaves One can of chicken breast, reserving the broth Accompaniment: cinnamon-spiced rice or basmati rice If using fresh okra, trim, leaving tops intact, being careful not to cut into pods. Heat oil in a 12-inch heavy skillet over moderately high heat until hot but not smoking, then sauté onion and garlic with ginger, curry powder, pepper, and chili powder, stirring, 2 minutes. Add tomatoes with their juice, chickpeas, and chicken with broth and boil, uncovered, stirring occasionally, 3 minutes. Stir in okra, salt, cloves, bay leaves, and simmer, covered (uncovered if thicker sauce desired), stirring occasionally, until okra is tender, about 10 minutes.

